76561198015748505,Recommended,494150,23988094,"Posted: 1 July, 2016",all,gessekai332,"As a person who did boxing as a hobby in college, I am very happy with this game and defintiely recommend it (especially because it is not a wave shooter like the rest of the VR games out there). I can block, bob and weave, counter punch when the computer throws punches (uppercuts, cross, hooks), so it's a great alternative to shadowboxing because you can practice defense at the same time. The blocking stamina mechanic is a good compromise so people dont cheese the system.However, since it is an early access game it is low on content (only one practice opponent and one real opponent), but I am sure the developer will add more soon since he has been very receptive to feedback and quick with his updates since his demo. The core mechanics are very solid and it is definitely worth the current price.EDIT: Adding a gameplay video of myself to give people an idea of what to expect.https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N1SnHwwtSrE"
,Recommended,494150,32740578,Posted: 24 June,all,Stal2k,"I've had about 5 years of combat sport experience. Full disclosure, it was MMA so that experience is more aligned with Muay Thai / American Kickboxing styles than classic boxing. While there are certainly differences between the styles, the 'feeling' of hitting someone in the face and emotions range felt during a match are probably pretty close. That being said I couldn't be happier to have something like this available.VR really opened the door to this level of immersion for sure, but all credit should go to the developer behind this. It's truly remarkable what he's accomplished. Getting the pacing and feeling of some of the nuances of the sport and actual act of fighting someone without actually having boxed himself is worth the price of admission alone.For perspective, I tried Knockout League and had to shut it off after the first fight for one simple reason; It committed the same sin virtually every other VR or motion controlled fighting game has before it.It did'nt take the user seriously, watered down physics that have more to do with a rhythm game or timing game on guardrails than a fight.Is ToTF perfect, the only thing missing is the concussion and black eyes? Of course not, but IMO it's leaps beyond anything else mechanically and ""experience"" wise. I know that is a word that gets thrown around a lot, but it's well earned for this title. For  example, even the 1st opponent takes me back to exactly what it was like to lightly spar with a training partner. Not too hard, not too slow, focusing on technique and movement.Pairing the current experience with a super responsive Dev, frequent updates that are almost always a love letter to the (active) community on the forums and you have a winner worth 3x the asking price. Personally, I can't wait to see where this game goes as we are treated to frequent and meaningful updates.Additional context, or to address some potential purchaser preconceptions:If you are looking into this as something to TEACH you to fight, I'll say this. It's not an instructional. HOWEVER. If you use some common sense, watch some instructional videos or books on the subject, you can ABSOLUTELY drill and refine technique and precision. This is valuable in a way that goes beyond pad or bag work as you can gauge actual distance and get used to 'picking apart' a defense. With the addition of the round system, it can also teach you good pacing. Just like real life, conserving your energy is a huge part of fight strategy.When I was actively training, I was unfortunate enough to be one of those people that felt bad for hitting someone too hard that I trained with. It's more common than you think, and with a game like this it allows you to get the 'feel' of things like (distance) timing and even evasion down without taking or doing any actual damage - except maybe to furniture or TVs if you don't strap in.The big exceptions to what isn't going to build good real world habits are some intermediate level footwork stuff like cut and gate steps based on AI tracking and/or play area limitations. You can still make these movements of course, but you don't get the same angles you would IRL if you really make someone miss. The only other thing this game doesn't do is actually hit you back."
76561198024518382,Recommended,494150,24119897,"Posted: 5 July, 2016",all,The Loafer,"For those concerned with ""yet another early access VR title""... you are right to be.  In other words, as advertised, this game is presently low on options with only 1 full opponent (not counting the training partner and the practice dummy manager).   There is a lot of work ahead for the dev.... However, let's also look at it from the POV of what we have.- A serious fun arcadish boxing game?  check- A way decent level of presence?  Check (I swear when he gets right in my face, I HAVE to back off!)- A workout and a half in trying to down the opponent? Check!- A dev that has already shown an ability to listen and quickly apply some upgrades to key areas?  Check!- Ugly Joe ugly enough?  With the update, checkmate!Serious fun, superior to the initial demo in every way and well worth purchasing.  Some tweaks still needed to the sound department (I want to hear the opponent grunt when I land some decent shots!) and the aformentioned need for other opponents but superior boxing game is attainable here when we look at the initial effort.Highly recommended!"
76561197988533180,Recommended,494150,32103296,Posted: 1 June,all,Shovelface,"THIS GAME IS GOING TO GIVE ME A SIX PACK!!!Errmmagerrrd, this game got me sweating. I tried it when it first released and maybe there just wasn't content released yet, because I only remember fighting the trainer. At the time, I thought meh. Glad I came back to it, especially the day after a big content patch.I used to compete at a very high level in wrestling, and this game inspired the same feeling of dread where your arms are burning with lactic acid and all you want is a second to rest, but your opponent keeps coming at you and you have no choice but to fight. Between rounds I would return to my corner and gasp for air, praying that the minute timer would slow down.As I write this I am pouring with sweat. The first fighter got me huffing and puffing, but the second fighter made dig deep into my soul and muster every ounce of grit I had to win. Took me several attempts, too.Not only did it require a tremendous amount of physicality, but you quickly learn that it's not just about throwing punches fast and hard. You will figure this out right away when you find yourself unconscious.Soon I was bobbing and weaving, throwing combos, body body head, head body uppercut, and soon it was my opponent that was hitting the mat.I'm on the third opponent now and have realized that it's going to take a serious amount of skill and endurance to beat. I have my punch force on the highest setting, so I might be challenging myself more than necessary, but I love a trial, and boy does this game bring it.10/10 my new favorite VR game. So glad I gave it a second chance.  Especially with pool party season coming up."
